WEBVTT

1
00:00:35.000 --> 00:00:53.000
<v Hiroshi Tanaka>Thanks everyone. This session is specifically about locking the Daimaru rescue plan before Monday&#x27;s sync. We already know the three objections; now we need a response strong enough that Daisuke can carry it into the procurement meeting next week.</v>

2
00:07:56.000 --> 00:08:17.000
<v Wei Zhang>The demo story should start with what Daimaru cares about: stock visibility across flagship floors and the speed of exception handling for store managers. I can show that with our prebuilt SAP connector and a Japanese-language operational dashboard, which lets us position the initial implementation as a 45-day pilot instead of a full transformation.</v>

3
00:15:17.000 --> 00:15:35.000
<v Priya Sharma>That shorter pilot story also helps because I can point to what we are doing in Mumbai. Two of my SMB customers accepted a phased deployment this week once we stopped selling the entire roadmap up front. The same logic should make Daimaru&#x27;s procurement team less nervous about the services line.</v>

4
00:22:38.000 --> 00:22:56.000
<v Aisha Rahman>Commercially, I recommend a 7 percent year-one concession paired with a flat year-two renewal and a 40-thousand services credit only if they sign by March 20. That keeps us inside the margin guardrail from Wednesday and gives Hiroshi something concrete to trade for urgency.</v>

5
00:29:59.000 --> 00:30:17.000
<v Mei Lin Tan>I agree, and I want the executive-sponsor section to sound outcome-based, not apologetic. Hiroshi, I can offer a direct call with the Daimaru CIO and commit to a monthly steering review for the first quarter after signature. That signals commitment without promising custom product work.</v>

6
00:37:20.000 --> 00:37:39.000
<v Hiroshi Tanaka>That is exactly what they need. Keisuke Mori told me yesterday that the customer&#x27;s internal debate is no longer whether they like us; it is whether we look decisive enough to trust during rollout. A 45-day pilot, a 7 percent year-one concession, and a sponsor cadence gives them a coherent reason to stay with us.</v>

7
00:44:41.000 --> 00:44:59.000
<v Wei Zhang>I will also add a runbook slide that shows how we cap implementation work at 95 thousand unless Daimaru asks for non-standard store integrations. That protects us from scope creep and makes the lower number credible.</v>

8
00:52:02.000 --> 00:52:20.000
<v Hiroshi Tanaka>Great. Final recap: Wei owns the demo and runbook, Aisha owns the pricing language, Mei Lin owns sponsor framing, and I will package all three into the customer memo tonight. By Monday&#x27;s week-two sync we should be ready to ask the Facilitator to turn this into a formal save proposal.</v>

